                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 10044/172.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">Leishman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-05-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 4, 1909</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Wilson says in view of the fact that the <hi rend="italic">North
                        Carolina</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Montana</hi> have proceeded so far on
                    their route to Turkey, it is hardly practicable at this late stage to recall
                    their orders. Says it is believed that the embassy will have no difficulty in
                    dispelling any misapprehension of the Turkish authorities as to the object of
                    the visit, which will be purely one of friendly courtesy to the new Government
                    now that good order has been restored and Americans are no longer in
                    jeopardy.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
